			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Do people in other classes actually know how bards solo?<a name="33693"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Apr 8 04 4:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>this is not the first time this has been dicussed. Disregarding class envy and all that crap, I think there is just a lot of misinformation about bards. People just don't know, not having had the experience of it. 
<br />
   As an example, I talked to a wizard friend a couple of nights ago about wizzy &amp; druid soloing vs. bard soloing, he rattled off a bunch of complete misconceptions that were totally off. This didn't all together surprise me, he's a very smart guy and has played the game for 3+ years, but he hasn't played a bard past level 30. If you were to put the classes side by side and look at it without intimate knowledge of each, it sure would seem that bards have the upper hand at soloing due to swarming and AEing, and the best bard ability of them all, being able to cast while moving. When you look closer, there is much more to it. Have you ever charm soloed PoP with a druid? I have, and I can tell you that once you get good at it, the xp is great, and IMO it's easier than swarming. This is all opinion, of course, and is based on my experiences. 
<br />
    When I get in trouble with my druid, I use the self only fast cast evac that druids get, when I get in trouble with my bard, I just hit a hotkey for my gate potion and take off running. If I have gate potions. How are these not comparable? Druids are limited to 4 targets at a time with thier DD spells, however, they do get PBAEs that will hit more than 4. So do bards. We are talking apples to apples here and all people see is the &quot;overpowered awesomeness of bards&quot; which isn't all together accurate. Think about how difficult and frustrating AEing can be. Sure it's great xp, incredible even, but how many times have you died doing it? Now if you play a druid, think about how long it took you to learn quadding...
<br />
Not as long right? I bet you didn't die as many times either, and consequently, you will not die as often during routine kites. Druids cannot cast while moving so I see there is an obvious advantage there, but also consider the fact that when using the druid version of malo (animal only just as thier charms) a charm will stick for an extended amount of time and is very mana efficient. Also consider the fact that druids get a pet haste that rivals chanty haste. 
<br />
    These observations may not be all together perfectly accurate but from my experiences playing both classes I can say that they are Very well balanced in the solo department. Feel free to challenge anything I've written here, I'd love to dicuss but let's keep this civil and keep in mind that no one here makes the rules, we just complain about them. 
<br />
<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-7.gif" border="0" alt="Perplexed" hspace="2" /></span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="SmallText"><hr size="1" align="left" width="15%">Scambon Greenbones<br>
62 Virtuoso<br>
ARo<br>
"I'll always be a dreamin man I don't have to understand.."<br>
<br>
The Wise Man learns more from the Fool than the Fool will ever learn from the Wise Man....</span></td>
